When setting up a <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/WordPress_Menu_User_Guide" target="menu_guide">menu</a> in <a href="wordpress.org" target="wordpress_org">WordPress</a>, you can add menu items that will allow you to show a specific category (or tag), which works great.  When I create a custom taxonomy (i.e.: for a custom post types), the WordPress menu page will also allow me to add a menu item to show a specific term, which works, well, not at all.

Let's say I create a <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Post_Types" target="post_types">Custom Post Type</a> called <tt>'portfolio'</tt>, along with a taxonomy called <tt>'port_work'</tt> with a rewrite slug of <tt>'work'</tt>.  Next I create a new <tt>'Portfolio'</tt> post, adding the tax term <tt>'Web Design'</tt>.  I then proceed to add an item to the menu that I believe should show all <tt>'portfolio'</tt> posts that have the <tt>'Web Design'</tt> term assigned to them, in the same way as categories and tags are handled by WordPress.

So far so good.  Except it doesn't work.  For this situation, WordPress generates a url of <tt>'site.com/work/web-design/'</tt>, which then proceeds to give me a 404 page.  Bummer.

Now this seems to me to be a rewrite issue.  Evidently, when creating a custom taxonomy, WordPress will not automatically create any rewrite rules for that taxonomy, even if I give it a rewrite slug (what else is the rewrite slug for??).  I guess they expect us to do it, which is really an issue for me because the <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Rewrite_API" target="wordpress_rewrite_api">Rewrite API</a> has always been, umm, less than clear to me.  Which means that it is not my first choice for a solution.  Yes, I can be an hard-headed idiot too, nobody has dibs on that.

So I decide to turn to the <tt>'<a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Plugin_API/Action_Reference/pre_get_posts" target="pre_get_posts">pre_get_posts</a>'</tt> hook, an old favorite of mine.  A little investigation shows that WordPress interprets the url <tt>'site.com/work/web-design/'</tt> into query vars of <tt>'array( 'name' =&gt; 'web-design', 'category_name' =&gt; 'work' )'</tt>.   With that information in hand, I can start writing a function I can use to hook into <tt>'pre_get_posts'</tt> and make it work the way I think it should.

First thing I do in that function is check to make sure I am not on an admin screen, using <tt>'<a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/is_admin" target="is_admin">is_admin()</a>'</tt>, and I also want to check that I am modifying the main query, using the <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Class_Reference/WP_Query" target="wp_query">WP_Query</a> method. And, since I use a php class to create the CPT, I'll add the function as a method in that class.
<pre><code>public function portfolio_pre_get_posts($query) {
   if ( ! is_admin &amp;&amp; $query-&gt;is_main_query() ) {
      // more code here
   }
}
</code></pre>
As evident in the declaration, WordPress passes the query object to all filters assigned to this hook. This initial setup should be pretty much standard for any function hooking into <tt>'pre_get_posts'</tt>. The actual <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Conditional_Tags" target="wp_conditionals">conditionals</a> may change, but the purpose is always the same. Make sure it only runs when it needs to. In that vein, I proceed to add a check for the post type.
<pre><code>$check = $query-&gt;get('post_type');
if ( $check &amp;&amp; in_array( $this-&gt;type, (array)$check ) ) {
   // more code here
}
</code></pre>
There are a couple of things I feel I need to point out here. First, by default WordPress does not includes CPTs in queries, which means I have to <a href="http://rtcenterprises.net/wordpress/wordpress-custom-post-types-and-wp_query/" target="cpt_and_wp_query">include them</a> myself if I want them to show up along with regular posts. Without that, this check is not needed. Also notice I am casting <tt>$check</tt> to an array. This is because <tt>$query-&gt;get('post_type')</tt> can return either a string or an array, and the cast is an easy solution.

Moving on to the query vars themselves, I first have to check that the taxonomy slug, stored in <tt>'category_name'</tt>, is actually a <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/taxonomy_exists" target="taxonomy_exists">valid taxonomy</a>. After that I check that the tax term, stored in <tt>'name'</tt>, is really a <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/term_exists" target="term_exists">valid term</a> for the taxonomy. If both of these checks succeed, then I know I am on the right track.
<pre><code>$tax = $query-&gt;get( 'category_name' );
if ( taxonomy_exists( "port_$tax" ) ) {
   $term = $query-&gt;get( 'name' );
   if ( term_exists( $term, "port_$tax" ) ) {
      // more code here
   }
}
</code></pre>
Notice the taxonomy slug I am passing in both function calls, where I am converting the rewrite slug back into the taxonomy slug. It is a small detail, but very important.  Be aware this only needs to be done if the rewrite slug is different from the taxonomy slug.  Of course you could end up doing this completely differently so YMMV.

At last I can move on to changing the query so that it does what I need. First I clear out the <tt>'name'</tt> and <tt>'category_name'</tt> vars since I already know these are causing the 404 error.
<pre><code>$query-&gt;set( 'name', '' );
$query-&gt;set( 'category_name', '' );
</code></pre>

Next I add in the correct vars where I need them.
<pre><code>$args = array( array( 'taxonomy' =&gt; "port_$tax", 'field' =&gt; 'slug', 'terms' =&gt; $term ) );
$query-&gt;set( 'tax_query', $args );
$this-&gt;add_post_type( $query );
</code></pre>

The <tt>$this-&gt;add_post_type</tt> is a function in the base class I use for CPTs.
<pre><code>protected function add_post_type( $query ) {
   $check = $query-&gt;get( 'post_type' );
   if ( empty( $check ) ) {
      $query-&gt;set( 'post_type', array( 'post', $this-&gt;type ) );
   } elseif ( ! ( (array)$check === $check ) ) {
      if ( $check !== $this-&gt;type ) {
         $query-&gt;set( 'post_type', array( $check, $this-&gt;type ) );
      }
   } elseif ( ! in_array( $this-&gt;type, $check ) ) {
      $check[] = $this-&gt;type;
      $query-&gt;set( 'post_type', $check );
   }
}
</code></pre>
You can view the explanation for the code in this function <a href="http://rtcenterprises.net/wordpress/wordpress-custom-post-types-and-wp_query/" target="cpt_and_wp_query">here</a>.

One last small detail to take care of. The <tt>'is_single'</tt> flag gets set by WordPress, which causes the <tt>'single.php'</tt> <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Templates" target="wp_templates">template</a> to be called. This can look a little strange if multiple posts are returned and the content.php template part gets used.
<pre><code>$query-&gt;is_single = '';
$query-&gt;is_singular = '';
</code></pre>
I reset the <tt>'is_singular'</tt> flag as well. So far I have not encountered any issues unsetting these, and not setting any other such flags, but I am aware problems are possible.

Here is the complete function:
<pre><code>public function portfolio_pre_get_posts( $query ) {
   if ( ! is_admin() &amp;&amp; $query-&gt;is_main_query() ) {
      $check = $query-&gt;get( 'post_type' );
      if ($check &amp;&amp; in_array( $this-&gt;type, (array)$check ) ) {
         $tax = $query-&gt;get( 'category_name' );
         if ( taxonomy_exists( "port_$tax" ) ) {
            $term = $query-&gt;get( 'name' );
            if ( term_exists( $term, "port_$tax" ) ) {
               $query-&gt;set( 'name', '' );
               $query-&gt;set( 'category_name', '' );
               $args = array( array( 'taxonomy' =&gt; "port_$tax", 'field' =&gt; 'slug', 'terms' =&gt; $term ) );
               $query-&gt;set( 'tax_query', $args );
               $this-&gt;add_post_type( $query );
               $query-&gt;is_single = '';
               $query-&gt;is_singular = '';
            }
         }
      }
   }
}
</code></pre>
And, if course, the hook itself:
<pre><code>add_filter( "pre_get_posts", array( $this, 'portfolio_pre_get_posts' ) );
</code></pre>
This goes in the class __construct method.

Well that's it. Using the Rewrite API would be better, but this works.

There is a real easy way to stop a taxonomy term from being deleted. And that is simply by not showing the delete option to start with.  If there is no delete option, then we don't have to worry about the term being deleted.

To start with, let's define what kind of terms we don't want deleted. In my experience, these terms tend to fall into one of two categories. The first is a term that is associated with a post, quite often of a custom post type. This is especially applicable when the term is tightly bound to the custom post type. Most anyone reading this post will understand the concept, or they probably wouldn't need to be here in the first place. The second type is a term that we simply don't want deleted, whether it is associated with a post or not. The reason we don't want the term deleted can be as varied as the term itself, depending on what we are using it for.

We can use the same methodology for both types of terms, but let's take a look at the first to start. We can accomplish our task using a combination of PHP and javascript. Let's start with the PHP:
<pre><code>function stop_term_deletion() {
  // find our location
  $screen = get_current_screen();
  // we only want the taxonomy screen
  if ($screen-&gt;base==='edit-tags') {
    // initialize empty array
    $keep_list = array();
    // get a list of all terms used by posts
    $term_list = get_terms($screen-&gt;taxonomy,'hide_empty=1');
    // did we get anything?
    if ($term_list) {
      // cycle through the results
      foreach($term_list as $term) {
        // store each term ID
        $keep_list[] = $term-&gt;term_id;
      }
    }
    // do we have anything?
    if ($keep_list) {
      // location of the js file
      $js_file = plugins_url('../js/tax_nodelete.js',__FILE__);
      // register script
      wp_register_script('term_nodelete',$js_file,array('jquery'),false,true);
      // pass our array to the script
      wp_localize_script('term_nodelete','term_list',$keep_list);
      // enqueue script
      wp_enqueue_script('term_nodelete');
    }
  }
}
// allows us to enqueue the js properly
add_action('admin_enqueue_scripts','stop_term_deletion');
</code></pre>
Let's go over what this code is accomplishing. We start by finding out where we are at by using WordPress's <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/get_current_screen" target="get_current_screen">get_current_screen()</a>. That way we are only processing the terms and loading the javascript if we are on the taxonomy screen. We might also want to expand the conditional like this: <code>if ( ( $screen-&gt;base == 'edit-tags' ) &amp;&amp; ( in_array( $screen-&gt;taxonomy, $nodelete_array ) ) )</code> where $nodelete_array is simply an array containing the slugs of all the taxonomies we might want to work with.

Next we use the <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/get_terms" target="get_terms">get_terms()</a> function, passing it 'hide_empty=1' as the second parameter, so that we only get the terms that are being used by a post. If we get a result back, we then populate the $keep_list array with the term ID numbers.

Now that we have a list of terms we want to keep, we move on to enqueuing the javascript. Here we are using <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/plugins_url" target="plugins_url">plugins_url()</a> to get the file location, although we might use another function depending on how we implement this function (or method). Notice that we are using the <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/wp_localize_script" target="wp_localize_script">wp_localize_script()</a> function to get the $keep_list array passed to the javascript.

Lastly, we use <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/add_action" target="add_action">add_action()</a>, utilizing the <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Plugin_API/Action_Reference/admin_enqueue_scripts" target="admin_enqueue_scripts">'admin_enqueue_scripts'</a> hook to insure that the function only fires in the dashboard, exactly where we need it to.

Before moving on to the javascript, let's discuss how we might handle the second kind of term. Understand that we need the term ID to make it work. Implementing that would go beyond the scope of this article, since it would need to be done when the terms are created, or possibly when the taxonomy is registered. Wrapping all this in a class would give the greatest flexibility, hence the code needed for the stop_term_deletion function might look something like this:
<pre><code>    if (!empty($this-&gt;tax_keep[$screen-&gt;taxonomy])) {
      foreach($this-&gt;tax_keep[$screen-&gt;taxonomy] as $term) {
        $keep_list[] = get_term_by('name',$term,$screen-&gt;taxonomy)-&gt;term_id;
      }
    }
</code></pre>
This particular snippet utilizes a class property array where the taxonomy slug is the index key for an array containing term names. It then uses <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/get_term_by" target="get_term_by">get_term_by()</a> to retrieve the term ID. This could have been accomplished in any number of different ways, just as long as we end up with a list of term IDs.

With that out of the way, let's move on to the javascript:
<pre><code>jQuery(document).ready(function() {
  for(var i=0,cnt=term_list.length;i&lt;cnt;i++) {
    jQuery('#tag-'+term_list[i]+' .row-actions .delete').remove();  // remove deletion span
    jQuery('#tag-'+term_list[i]+' label').remove(); // remove checkbox label
    jQuery('#tag-'+term_list[i]+' input').remove(); // remove checkbox
  }
});
</code></pre>
This code is written for WordPress 4.2.2, and is completely dependent on the table structure on the edit-tag screen. It looks for the table row that has an id of 'tag-{$termID}', and then looks in that row for a span with a class of 'delete'. This span, which contains the delete anchor, is then removed from the DOM.  Also removed is the bulk action checkbox and corresponding label.  Anyone viewing the screen never sees the delete option, and thus cannot delete the term.

Of course, all this does not prevent the term from being deleted in some other fashion, but until the WordPress devs see fit to provide a hook, or some other method, to allow us programmers to prevent deletion of a term, then this will have to do. I hope this article was helpful to you.

So long, and thanks for all the fish. Now if I can just remember where I left my sonic screwdriver...

