I really like the datepicker in jQuery's UI. Using it allows me to show the date in any local format needed, while using the altField and altFormat options allows me to save the time as a timestamp in a hidden field, completely separate from the displayed date.

Sounds like a good plan, yes?  I wish it were that easy.  The problem is that while I need a unix timestamp, which has been defined as being in seconds, it seems the datepicker saves in milliseconds. Really?  Why?  There is a two year old <a href="https://bugs.jqueryui.com/ticket/10001" target="_blank">ticket</a> open on this issue. wtf?

In order for the timestamp to be useful to me, I have to do a conversion somewhere along the way.  I can't use the value as is, because I would end up having to convert it every time I need to use it for a date calculation.  What if I forget?  I could do the conversion before saving it to the db.  With different names for different date fields I would need to track each date field in some fashion.  What if I forget when I add a new date field?  And my current project has a lot of date fields.

It just seemed to me that the best way to handle the conversion is to do it when the new date is input. I first tried to attach an onchange event to the hidden field.  Silly me.  Turns out that the datepicker doesn't trigger it when the new value is put in, at least not in the browser I'm using - firefox 45.1.0, as of the date of this post. Of course the onchange is triggered when attached to the visible field. This works, but is not what I would consider an optimum solution. What about when I need a different onchange for the date field? I haven't had to solve that one yet.

My current solution involves three parts, the first part in PHP. This is the function I use to display a date:

<pre><code>public function date($echo=true) {
    $html = "&lt;label for='skip_me_{$this-&gt;name}'&gt;" . $this-&gt;prompt(false) . "  ";
    $html.= "&lt;input type='text' size='10' class='form-control inline date'"; $html.= " id='skip_me_{$this-&gt;name}' name='skip_me_{$this-&gt;name}'";
    $date = $this-&gt;form_date();
    $html.= " value='$date'";
    $html.= " data-altfield='{$this-&gt;name}' onchange='fix_jquery_datepicker(this)'&gt;";
    $html.= "&lt;input type='hidden' id='{$this-&gt;name}' name='{$this-&gt;name}'";
    $unix = $this-&gt;deform_date();
    $html.= " value='$unix'&gt;";
    if ($echo) { echo $html; } else { return $html; }
  }</code></pre>

As you can see this is a method in a class. The class in question is being used to handle how any particular field is displayed. I won't go into that in this post. I hope the code is self-explanatory, except for perhaps the 'skip_me_', the prompt() call, and the 'data-altfield' attribute (which I'll explain further down). Also, there are a couple of helper functions I wrote to help keep the code backwardly compatible with the database, <code>form_date()</code> and <code>deform_date()</code>:

<pre><code>public function deform_date() {  #  convert to unix timestamp
    $check = intval($this-&gt;value,10);
    if ($check&lt;3000) { $unix = strtotime($this-&gt;value);
      if ($unix) return $unix;
    }
    return $this-&gt;value;
  }

  public function form_date($reset=false) {  #  convert to formatted date
    //  check for unix time before formatting
    $check = intval($this-&gt;value,10);
    if ($reset &amp;&amp; $check&lt;3000) { $check = strtotime($this-&gt;value);
    }
    if ($check&gt;3000) {  #  large year value - assumed unix time
      global $data;
      return date($data['dateformat'],$check);
    }
    return $this-&gt;value;
  }</code></pre>

These functions work for my situation, but they make a couple of assumptions. <code>deform_date()</code>, which is supposed to check for, or generate, a unix timestamp, assumes that there will be no database entries occurring in Jan 1970 or earlier. It also uses <a href="http://php.net/manual/en/function.strtotime.php" target="_blank"><code>strtotime()</code></a>, which expects any date to be in a format it can parse. <code>form_date()</code> make the same date range assumption, as well as using <code>strtotime()</code>. They aren't great, but they do what I need.

When it came to the javascript, I use this for my datepicker defaults:

<pre><code>$.datepicker.setDefaults({
    autoSize: true,
    buttonImageOnly: true,
    buttonImage: mydata.siteURL+"/images/cal.gif",
    buttonText: "Calendar",
    dateFormat: lesson.dateform,
    gotoCurrent: true,
    showOn: "both",
  });</code></pre>

Rather than using this line to assign the datepicker:

<pre><code>$(selector).datepicker();</code></pre>

I ended up using this function:

<pre><code>function jquery_datepicker(selector) {
  $(selector).each(function() {
    var field = $(this).attr('data-altfield');
    if (field) {
      $(this).datepicker({ altField:  '#'+field,
                           altFormat: '@' });
    } else {
      $(this).datepicker();
    }
  });
}</code></pre>

Notice that it will only use the altF* options if the data-altfield attribute is present. Otherwise it defaults to the standard assignment.

Finally, the solution to the initial problem:

<pre><code>// jquery datepicker inserts milliseconds instead of seconds
function fix_jquery_datepicker(el) {
  var ele = el.getAttribute('data-altfield');
  var hid = document.getElementById(ele);
  if (hid &amp;&amp; (hid.value / 1462507200 &gt; 500)) {  //  is it in milliseconds?
    hid.value = hid.value / 1000;
  }
}</code></pre>

First I retrieve the altField name from the data attribute.  Then I check to insure the value doesn't get converted more than once. The number I use as the divisor is arbitrary, just something I picked.

In fact, a lot of my solution is tailored to the situation. I hope that my code is helpful in tailoring your own solution to your own problem.  Good Luck!

By default, <a href="wordpress.org" target="wordpress_org">WordPress</a> does not include <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Post_Types" target="post_types">Custom Post Types</a> in any query.  Which means if a developer wants the CPT to <a href="https://wordpress.org/support/topic/custom-post-type-posts-not-displayed" target="custom_post_type_display">show up</a> in lists with the regular posts, then that behavior needs to be accounted for.

I always use a php class for my CPTs, so here's how I would begin to write a method so that my CPT is included in the regular queries:

<pre><code>public function pre_get_posts($query) {
   if ((!is_admin() && $query->is_main_query() && !($query->is_page())) || $query->is_feed) {
      // more code goes here
   }
}
</code></pre>

I usually name methods such as this the same as the hook slug, just as a reminder when I may have to edit the method at some later date.  The <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Conditional_Tags" target="wp_conditionals">conditionals</a> serve to make sure I only alter the correct queries.  The first, <tt><a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/is_admin" target="is_admin">is_admin()</a></tt>, ensures that I am only modifying queries originating on the public side of the website.  The next three conditionals use WP_Query methods instead of the function calls.  Of these, <tt>$query->is_main_query()</tt>, makes sure I am not modifying some custom query in a widget somewhere.  The second, <tt>$query->is_page()</tt>, keeps me from trying to mess with a page's content.  The last conditional, <tt>$query->is_feed</tt>, ensures that the CPT is always included in a feed query.  I have seen some people recommend use of the <tt><a href="https://developer.wordpress.org/reference/functions/is_feed/" target="is_feed">is_feed()</a></tt> function.  However, perusal of the source code for that, and similar functions, indicates that it will not return a correct value until <i>after</i> the query has been run, which has not happened yet.  That is the main reason you should always use the <tt>$query</tt> methods and properties in functions like this one.

With that out of the way, I will move on to the meat of the function:

<pre><code>$check = $query->get('post_type');
if (empty($check)) {
  $query->set('post_type',array('post',$this->type));
} elseif (!((array)$check===$check)) {
   if ($check!==$this->type) { $query->set('post_type',array($check,$this->type)); }
} elseif (!in_array($this->type,$check)) {
   $check[] = $this->type;
   $query->set('post_type',$check);
}
</code></pre>

A note here about the <tt>$query->get('post_type')</tt> call:  The vastly large majority of the time it will return a string.  Sometimes though, it will return an array.  This occurs because of other CPTs being used by the site that are also including themselves in the main query.  This must be taken into account.  To do this, I first check to see if a post type has been assigned.  While I would normally expect this to be the case, if this has been bungled by another plugin or the active theme, I want to be able to recover from it.  My next check just looks to see if an array has been returned, while the last check looks to see if the CPT is already included in the query and if not then include it.

Here is the complete method:

<pre><code>public function pre_get_posts($query) {
    if ((!is_admin() && $query->is_main_query() && !($query->is_page())) || $query->is_feed) {
      $check = $query->get('post_type');
      if (empty($check)) {
        $query->set('post_type',array('post',$this->type));
      } elseif (!((array)$check==$check)) {
        if ($check!==$this->type) { $query->set('post_type',array($check,$this->type)); }
      } elseif (!in_array($this->type,$check)) {
        $check[] = $this->type;
        $query->set('post_type',$check);
      }
   }
}
</code></pre>

And the filter call:

<pre><code>add_filter('pre_get_posts', array($this,'pre_get_posts'),5);   #  run early - priority 5
</code></pre>

If you have any insight on this,  please leave me a note.  I am always interested in improving my code.

While I rarely find PHP <a href="http://php.net/manual/en/language.oop5.traits.php" target="php_trait">traits</a> very useful, there are some situations where I think they have some use. Case in point is the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singleton_pattern" target="singleton_pattern">singleton</a>. And, no, I am not going to join the 'Singletons are Evil' debate. This post is for those people who may occasionally find a use case for a singleton. With that said, here's my singleton trait:
<pre><code>trait Singleton_Trait {

    protected static $abort__construct;
    private static $instances = array();

    public static function instance() {
        return self::get_instance();
    }

    public static function get_instance( $args = array() ) {
        $class = get_called_class();
        if ( ! isset( self::$instances[ $class ] ) ) {
            $instance = new $class( $args );
            if ( static::$abort__construct ) {
                static::$abort__construct = false;
            } else {
                self::$instances[ $class ] = $instance;
            }
        }
        return ( isset( self::$instances[ $class ] ) ) ? self::$instances[ $class ] : null;
    }

    private function __clone() { }
    private function __sleep() { }
    private function __wakeup() { }

}
</code></pre>

This example avoids the issue of having to declare the $instance variable in any child classes.  There are actually two entry points for the singleton, instance() and get_instance( $args ).  The get_instance() call is for those times when parameters need to be passed to the class constructor.  The instance() call is simply for getting the instance when no parameters are needed, or after any required parameters have already been passed to the class in a get_instance() call.

Also, notice the <tt>$abort__construct</tt> property, spelled with two underlines.  This property allows a constructor to force an abort if some required condition is not met.

Just my 2 cents...

First the bad news:

Starting with version 4.4.0, WordPress had a filter named 'rest_enabled' that allowed you to turn off the REST API.  This was deprecated in version 4.7.0, as per this WordPress <a href="https://core.trac.wordpress.org/ticket/38446" target="_blank">ticket</a>.

Now the good news:

This does not mean that the API cannot be disabled.  It just means that the 'rest_enabled' filter can no longer be used to do so.  WordPress recommends using <a href="https://developer.wordpress.org/rest-api/using-the-rest-api/frequently-asked-questions/#require-authentication-for-all-requests" target="_blank">this method</a>.  Here is another means of disabling the WordPress REST API:

<pre><code>function clear_rest_api_endpoints() {
   return array();
}
add_filter( 'rest_endpoints', 'clear_rest_api_endpoints' );
</code></pre>


This disables all endpoints and will cause this json object to be returned:

<pre><code>{"code":"rest_no_route","message":"No route was found matching the URL and request method","data":{"status":404}}
</code></pre>

This filter could also be used to control which endpoints that you allow access to, by filtering which endpoints are returned.

One of the really frustrating things about working with the <a href="https://developer.wordpress.org/themes/customize-api/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">WordPress Customizer Javascript API</a> is an apparent lack of decent documentation.  The official WordPress position is "read the source code".  Um...Okay.  Try it.  I hope you can glean more out of it than I did.

Googling, I found quite a bit on how to show/hide a page element, including these two articles from <a href="https://tommcfarlin.com/hiding-elements-wordpress-theme-customizer/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Tom McFarlin</a> and <a href="https://make.xwp.co/2016/07/24/dependently-contextual-customizer-controls/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Weston Ruter</a>.  However there wasn't a whole lot on how to hide and show customizer controls based on other control settings.  The most useful resource I found was <code>wp-content/themes/twentyseventeen/assets/js/customize-controls.js</code>.  Yep, I read the source code.  Other resources I located included this <a href="https://wordpress.stackexchange.com/questions/286268/is-it-possible-to-conditionally-displaying-and-hiding-of-customizer-controls-for?rq=1" rel="noopener" target="_blank">WordPress StackExchange question</a> and <a href="https://gist.github.com/westonruter/26ea57217efc074b2a948e32a61897f9" rel="noopener" target="_blank">it's gist</a>, <a href="https://www.gavick.com/blog/contextual-controls-theme-customizer" rel="noopener" target="_blank">gavick.com</a>, <a href="https://code.tutsplus.com/tutorials/customizer-javascript-apis-panel-section-and-control--cms-27218" rel="noopener" target="_blank">envatotuts+</a>, <a href="https://wordpress.stackexchange.com/questions/145338/theme-customizer-conditional-controls" rel="noopener" target="_blank">another WordPress StackExchange post</a>, <a href="https://maddisondesigns.com/2017/05/the-wordpress-customizer-a-developers-guide-part-1/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Anthony Hortin</a> with <a href="https://maddisondesigns.com/2017/05/the-wordpress-customizer-a-developers-guide-part-2/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Part 2</a>, <a href="https://florianbrinkmann.com/en/3783/conditional-displaying-and-hiding-of-customizer-controls-via-javascript/" target="florian_brinkmann" rel="nofollow noopener">Florian Brinkmann</a> and <a href="https://gist.github.com/FlorianBrinkmann/e44e62eb77333e8e080d7ac605b91da0" target="florian_brinkmann_gist" rel="nofollow noopener">his gist</a>, and <a href="http://www.jasong-designs.com/2017/05/04/hide-show-controls-wordpress-customizer/" target="jason_g_designs" rel="nofollow noopener">Jason G. Designs</a>.

What I wanted to able to do was programmatically tell the javascript what to hide/show, and when.  Plus, I wanted to be able to hide a control if a certain option is chosen, as well as be able to show a control only if a certain option has been chosen.

So I started by creating an array that would contain all the controls I wanted to hide or show, and the conditions under which it needed to happen.
 
<pre class="lang:php decode:true " title="Customizer Controls" >$options = array(
   // hide 'sidebar_fluidity' if 'sidebar_position' = 'none'
   'sidebar_fluidity' => array(
      'control' => 'sidebar_position',
      'action'  => 'hide',
      'setting' => 'none'
   ),
   // hide 'sidebar_mobile' if 'sidebar_position' = 'none'
   'sidebar_mobile' => array(
      'control' => 'sidebar_position',
      'action'  => 'hide',
      'setting' => 'none'
   ),
   // show 'social_icons' if 'use_social_icons' = 'yes'
   'social_icons' => array(
      'control' => 'use_social_icons',
      'action'  => 'show',
      'setting' => 'yes'
   );
);</pre>



Next task was passing that array along to the the javascript, using <a href="https://developer.wordpress.org/reference/functions/wp_localize_script/" rel="noopener" target="_blank"><code>wp_localize_script()</code></a>.

<pre class="lang:php decode:true " title="Localize Controls" >wp_enqueue_script( 'fluid-customizer.js',  get_theme_file_uri( 'js/customizer.js' ),   null, '2.3.0', true);
$options = apply_filters( 'fluid_customize_controls_localization', $options );
wp_localize_script( 'fluid-customizer.js', 'fluid_customize', $options );</pre>


The <code>apply_filters</code> call is used to add any other controls to the array as needed.

The final piece of the puzzle was the javascript that does the work.

<pre class="lang:js decode:true " title="Javascript Loop" >(function () {

   var api = wp.customize;

   /**
    * Run function when customizer is ready.
    */
   api.bind('ready', function () {

      for ( var target in fluid_customize ) {
         api( fluid_customize[ target ].control, function( setting ) {
            api.control( target, function( control ) {
               var visibility = function() {
                  if ( fluid_customize[ control.id ].action === 'hide' ) {
                     if ( fluid_customize[ control.id ].setting === setting.get() ) {
                        control.container.slideUp( 180 );
                     } else {
                        control.container.slideDown( 180 );
                     }
                  }
                  if ( fluid_customize[ control.id ].action === 'show' ) {
                     if ( fluid_customize[ control.id ].setting === setting.get() ) {
                        control.container.slideDown( 180 );
                     } else {
                        control.container.slideUp( 180 );
                     }
                  }
               };
               visibility();
               setting.bind( visibility );
            } );
         } );
      }
   } );
} )();</pre>


The javascript is largely derived from the <code>wp-content/themes/twentyseventeen/assets/js/customize-controls.js</code> file that I referred to earlier.

Well, that's my contribution to hiding/showing customizer controls.  Happy Coding!

